### ============================================================================
### service-policy — ACTION CATALOGUE walkthrough (ADR-028)
###   POST   /v1/apps/{app}/action-catalogue                 declare a resource type
###   GET    /v1/apps/{app}/action-catalogue                 list the whole catalogue
###   GET    /v1/apps/{app}/action-catalogue/{resourceType}  one entry (+ ETag)
###   PUT    /v1/apps/{app}/action-catalogue/{resourceType}  replace the action set
###   DELETE /v1/apps/{app}/action-catalogue/{resourceType}  undeclare it
###
### Open in VS Code (REST Client) or IntelliJ HTTP Client; run top-down.
### Start the app first:  ./mvnw quarkus:dev    (Docker running for MongoDB + OIDC)
###
### WHAT THE CATALOGUE IS FOR (ADR-028):
###   An application declares, per resource type, the set of actions that exist:
###       kronia / document → [create, read, update, delete]
###       kronia / request  → [create, read, submit, approve, reject]
###   Two things follow, and they are the whole point:
###   1) `actions: ["*"]` in a policy is EXPANDED AT AUTHORING against this list and
###      the explicit list is stored. `*` never reaches storage, never reaches the
###      evaluator. Adding a verb later therefore changes NO existing policy — widening
###      one is an explicit, versioned authoring act.
###   2) A policy naming a verb the app does not declare is rejected at authoring with
###      400 INVALID_POLICY. Declare the vocabulary first, then write policies about it.
###
### /evaluate NEVER reads the catalogue — this adds nothing to the hot path.
###
### Admin-gated (ADR-013) and nested under the app (ADR-026): `app` must NOT appear in
### any request body (sending it → 400 BAD_REQUEST, even if it matches the path).
### Writes are conditional: If-Match: "<revision>" (the ETag from a GET).
###   Missing If-Match → 428 ; stale → 412.
### Errors are RFC 9457 application/problem+json (see docs/ERRORS.md).
### ============================================================================

@host = http://localhost:8080
@auth_admin = Bearer {{admin_jwt}}


### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 1) DECLARE the vocabulary of "document" in app "rh"  →  201 Created
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### Note: NO "app" field in the body — the path carries it. And no "*" in the list:
### the catalogue IS the explicit set that "*" expands to.
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/action-catalogue
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "resourceType": "document",
  "actions": ["create", "read", "update", "delete"]
}

### EXPECTED  201 Created, ETag: "1"
### { "app": "rh", "resourceType": "document",
###   "actions": ["create","read","update","delete"], "revision": 1 }
### `app` IS returned in responses (the server supplies it) — it is only absent from
### request bodies.


### 2) DECLARE a second resource type — vocabularies stay apart per resource type
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/action-catalogue
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "resourceType": "request",
  "actions": ["create", "read", "submit", "approve", "reject"]
}

### EXPECTED  201 Created, ETag: "1"
### "approve" belongs to `request`, not to `document`. A catalogue keyed by app alone
### would have mixed them and made "*" on a document expand to "approve".


### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 3) LIST the whole catalogue of the app  →  200
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
GET {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/action-catalogue
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}

### EXPECTED  200 OK
### { "entries": [
###     { "app":"rh", "resourceType":"document", "actions":[…], "revision":1 },
###     { "app":"rh", "resourceType":"request",  "actions":[…], "revision":1 }
### ]}
### Sorted by resourceType. DELIBERATELY NOT PAGINATED: a catalogue is a bounded
### vocabulary (tens of entries), and its consumers — wildcard expansion and permission
### enumeration — need it WHOLE. A partial catalogue is not a smaller answer, it is a
### wrong one.


### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 4) GET one entry  →  200, read the ETag (needed to write)
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
GET {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/action-catalogue/document
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}

### EXPECTED  200 OK.  Headers: ETag: "1"


### ============================================================================
### WHAT THE CATALOGUE DOES TO AUTHORING — the reason it exists
### ============================================================================

### 5) Create a policy with actions ["*"]  →  201, but "*" is NOT what gets stored
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "policyId": "doc-access",
  "version": 1,
  "resourceType": "document",
  "actions": ["*"],
  "combiningAlgorithm": "DENY_OVERRIDES",
  "defaultEffect": "DENY",
  "rules": [
    { "id": "assigned-access", "effect": "PERMIT",
      "condition": { "type": "comparison", "op": "IN",
        "left": {"ref": "subject.id"}, "right": {"ref": "resource.attr.assignees"} } }
  ]
}

### EXPECTED  201 Created


### 6) …read the stored version back — the explicit list, in catalogue order
GET {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies/doc-access/versions/1
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}

### EXPECTED  200  →  "actions": ["create","read","update","delete"]   ← no "*"
### THIS is the fail-safe property: if someone adds "export" to the catalogue tomorrow,
### this policy still governs exactly these four verbs. Widening it requires appending
### a new version — an explicit, audited act.


### 7) 400 INVALID_POLICY — an action the app does not declare
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "policyId": "bad-verb",
  "version": 1,
  "resourceType": "document",
  "actions": ["read", "export", "shred"],
  "combiningAlgorithm": "DENY_OVERRIDES",
  "defaultEffect": "DENY",
  "rules": []
}

### EXPECTED  400  code: "INVALID_POLICY"
### invalidParams: one entry PER unknown action (field "actions") — "export" AND
### "shred", so the author fixes them in one pass rather than one round-trip each.


### 8) 400 INVALID_POLICY — "*" mixed with a named verb
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "policyId": "mixed-wildcard",
  "version": 1,
  "resourceType": "document",
  "actions": ["*", "read"],
  "combiningAlgorithm": "DENY_OVERRIDES",
  "defaultEffect": "DENY",
  "rules": []
}

### EXPECTED  400  →  "'*' must be the only element of 'actions'"
### "*" means "all of them"; mixing it with a verb is a contradiction, not a union.


### 9) 400 INVALID_POLICY — a resource type with no catalogue at all
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "policyId": "undeclared-type",
  "version": 1,
  "resourceType": "invoice",
  "actions": ["*"],
  "combiningAlgorithm": "DENY_OVERRIDES",
  "defaultEffect": "DENY",
  "rules": []
}

### EXPECTED  400  →  "no action catalogue for resource type 'invoice' in this app;
###                    declare the catalogue before authoring"
### An empty catalogue blocks authoring, which is correct: "*" against nothing would
### silently produce an empty action list — a policy that governs nothing.


### 10) Simulation validates identically (ADR-027 + ADR-028)
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies:simulate
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "policy": {
    "policyId": "draft", "version": 1, "resourceType": "document",
    "actions": ["*"], "combiningAlgorithm": "DENY_OVERRIDES", "defaultEffect": "DENY",
    "rules": [
      { "id": "assigned-access", "effect": "PERMIT",
        "condition": { "type": "comparison", "op": "IN",
          "left": {"ref": "subject.id"}, "right": {"ref": "resource.attr.assignees"} } }
    ]
  },
  "request": {
    "action": "document:read",
    "resource": { "type": "document", "id": "d1", "attributes": { "assignees": ["test-user"] } }
  }
}

### EXPECTED  200  →  allowed: true
### The candidate's "*" is expanded before evaluation, so what you simulate is what
### would be persisted. An uncatalogued action here is the same 400 INVALID_POLICY as
### on create — the simulator never decides on a draft you could not save.


### ============================================================================
### CHANGING A CATALOGUE — adding is free, removing is guarded
### ============================================================================

### 11) PUT — ADD a verb.  Always safe: no existing policy changes meaning.
### The body is the FULL new set (a replace, not a merge).
PUT {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/action-catalogue/document
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json
If-Match: "1"

{ "actions": ["create", "read", "update", "delete", "export"] }

### EXPECTED  200 OK, ETag: "2"
### doc-access (step 5) still governs only the original four verbs — "export" reaches
### it only if someone appends a new version. That is the ADR-028 guarantee.


### 12) 428 PRECONDITION_REQUIRED — write without If-Match
PUT {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/action-catalogue/document
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{ "actions": ["create", "read"] }

### EXPECTED  428  code: "PRECONDITION_REQUIRED"
### (An unparseable If-Match, e.g. If-Match: "abc", is refused the same way: never a
### blind write.)


### 13) 412 PRECONDITION_FAILED — stale If-Match
PUT {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/action-catalogue/document
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json
If-Match: "1"

{ "actions": ["create", "read"] }

### EXPECTED  412  code: "PRECONDITION_FAILED"  (extension: currentRevision: 2)
### The revision moved to 2 in step 11. Reload, re-apply, retry — the lost-update guard.
### Note: no `policyId` member here; a catalogue entry has no policy id.


### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 14) Activate doc-access, so an ACTIVE policy governs "delete"
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
GET {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies/doc-access
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}

### → read the ETag ("0" right after create), then:

POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies/doc-access/activate
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json
If-Match: "0"

{ "version": 1 }

### EXPECTED  200 OK, ETag: "1"


### 15) 409 ACTION_IN_USE — remove a verb an ACTIVE policy still governs
### Use the entry's current ETag ("2" after step 11) as If-Match.
PUT {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/action-catalogue/document
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json
If-Match: "2"

{ "actions": ["create", "read", "update", "export"] }

### EXPECTED  409  code: "ACTION_IN_USE"
### {
###   "detail": "Action(s) [delete] of resource type 'document' in app 'rh' are
###              referenced by active policies [doc-access].",
###   "policyIds": ["doc-access"]        ← exactly what stands in the way
### }
### Nothing was written: the entry still lists "delete". This is the safe default
### ADR-028 leaves in place until a deprecation contract is decided.
### An INACTIVE policy never blocks — it decides nothing.


### 16) 409 ACTION_IN_USE — deleting the entry is removing every action at once
DELETE {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/action-catalogue/document
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
If-Match: "2"

### EXPECTED  409  code: "ACTION_IN_USE"  (same policyIds)


### 17) Deactivate the policy — now nothing governs "delete"
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies/doc-access/deactivate
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json
If-Match: "1"

{ "changeReason": "retiring before narrowing the catalogue" }

### EXPECTED  200 OK, ETag: "2"


### 18) …and the same removal now succeeds
PUT {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/action-catalogue/document
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json
If-Match: "2"

{ "actions": ["create", "read", "update", "export"] }

### EXPECTED  200 OK, ETag: "3"  →  "delete" is gone from the vocabulary


### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 19) DELETE the entry  →  204 No Content
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
DELETE {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/action-catalogue/document
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
If-Match: "3"

### EXPECTED  204 No Content (empty body)
### Afterwards, policies of resourceType "document" can no longer be authored in this
### app until the catalogue is declared again. Existing policies are untouched —
### their actions were expanded and stored long ago.


### ============================================================================
### PER-APP ISOLATION (ADR-024/026) — the catalogue is scoped like everything else
### ============================================================================

### 20) The SAME resourceType in a DIFFERENT app → 201, not 409
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/nami/action-catalogue
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{ "resourceType": "document", "actions": ["read", "publish"] }

### EXPECTED  201 Created — identity is (app, resourceType). Two independent entries
### with independent action sets and independent revisions.


### 21) …and an action declared in one app is UNKNOWN in another
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "policyId": "cross-app-verb",
  "version": 1,
  "resourceType": "document",
  "actions": ["publish"],
  "combiningAlgorithm": "DENY_OVERRIDES",
  "defaultEffect": "DENY",
  "rules": []
}

### EXPECTED  400  code: "INVALID_POLICY"
### "publish" exists in nami's vocabulary, not in rh's. No shared base catalogue —
### ADR-024's isolation stance holds here too.


### 22) 404 CATALOGUE_ENTRY_NOT_FOUND — another app's entry is invisible
GET {{host}}/v1/apps/kronia/action-catalogue/document
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}

### EXPECTED  404  code: "CATALOGUE_ENTRY_NOT_FOUND"


### ============================================================================
### REMAINING ERROR CONTRACTS
### ============================================================================

### 23) 409 CATALOGUE_ENTRY_ALREADY_EXISTS — declaring a resource type twice
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/nami/action-catalogue
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{ "resourceType": "document", "actions": ["read"] }

### EXPECTED  409  code: "CATALOGUE_ENTRY_ALREADY_EXISTS"
### Create is not an update — use PUT to change the action set.


### 24) 400 BAD_REQUEST — `app` in the body (ADR-026)
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/nami/action-catalogue
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{ "app": "nami", "resourceType": "ticket", "actions": ["read"] }

### EXPECTED  400  →  "'app' must not be present in the body; it is determined by the path."
### Rejected for EXISTING, not for disagreeing.


### 25) 400 BAD_REQUEST — "*" as a catalogue action
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/nami/action-catalogue
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{ "resourceType": "ticket", "actions": ["*"] }

### EXPECTED  400  →  "'*' is not a catalogue action; the catalogue is the explicit
###                    set it expands to."
### Also 400: an empty `actions`, a blank element, a duplicate element, a blank
### `resourceType`. These are BAD_REQUEST, not INVALID_POLICY — a catalogue entry is
### not a policy document.


### 26) 403 FORBIDDEN — non-admin token
GET {{host}}/v1/apps/nami/action-catalogue
Authorization: Bearer {{jwt}}

### EXPECTED  403  code: "FORBIDDEN"  (every catalogue operation is admin-gated)


### ============================================================================
### HOW TO OBTAIN TOKENS (dev)
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### In quarkus:dev the OIDC dev services start a Keycloak. Get tokens via the Dev UI
### (http://localhost:8080/q/dev) → OIDC. {{admin_jwt}} must carry the admin marker
### (role "authz-admin" by default; configurable per ADR-013).
###
### RELATED FILES:
###   lifecycle-walkthrough.http   full policy lifecycle (starts by declaring a catalogue)
###   evaluation-endpoints.http    /evaluate, /evaluate/batch, /permissions
### ============================================================================
